ter and memory pin to map the lattice’s pulse without damaging it.\",\n        \"Expose or document any illegal star-metal clauses in Indigosatchel contracts encountered on-site.\"\n      ],\n      \"dialogue\": [\n        {\"speaker\": \"Brina Coil\", \"lines\": \"We bind fire to purpose and we have sworn our forges will not be coaxed to make blades that thirst for nothing but blood. The city needs bearings that do not seize and sluices that sing true, not some greedy hole torn in a hymn that steadies the river’s breathing. Walk with us at the Fault and keep tempers from running like molten glass, because a single careless word can ripple the lattice and crack more than stone. If we can prove to all eyes that the lattice is a song and not a seam, even the coin-counters may listen when silence is dearer than metal. I will place a prism register in your hands and a memory pin at your heart, and I ask you to be the hinge that does not grind when pressure comes. Should shadowed clauses arrive wrapped in smiles, we will not sign what we cannot sing to our apprentices with clean throats.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Thorek Brimvauld\", \"lines\": \"Our kettles sing true because we listen to stone when it is quiet and when it is storming, not because we bully it with picks and writs. I do not trust your Ledgerfolk nor your market queens, for I have seen obligations turned into garrotes, but I have watched an oath-bound man stand fast in flood and keep a bridge from breaking. Draw me proof and swear me witness that your city will not steal star-metal from under our noses while preaching restraint, and I will see your forges have salt and iron through winter without a single wagon delayed. These ledges are our grandparents’ bones as much as they are your city’s lifeline, so no chips pocketed, no shards palmed, and no notes hummed that you do not admit. The lattice wakes when you lie to it, and when stone wakes angry it does not go back to sleep for a dozen winters. Keep your words square, your boots sure, and your fellows watched, and I will keep my crews’ tempers banked like coals under ash.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Mereth Tydel\", \"lines\": \"The Temple teaches that some flows are covenant and some are trespass, and the lattice beneath the Fault has the feel of covenant bound in the world’s first ink. Walk calmly, keep your breath measured, and let the augurs’ bells set the pace so that our presence is a courtesy and not a raid. If a note rises beneath your feet that you do not know, do not follow it with your voice, for echo is a hunger as surely as any appetite. We bless this survey for observation and remembrance, not extraction, and an oath will be spoken that any gleaned profit shall be shared in health and safety, not weaponized for rivalry. Aren Siltwarden, I witnessed your oath once when your name was a thread in my hands, and I ask you to hold the memory of that river-quiet now against all clever bargains. Bring back truth like clear water in a basin, and we will pour it for all to see without salt of shame.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Quill Vess\", \"lines\": \"I care little for the vanity of coin, and less for the pride of those who count it, but I care for the Weir whose song must remain steady or the city learns to tread water in its sleep. The lattice under the Fault hums on a frequency our gates answer to in their dreams, and a wrong chord there would make our sluices stutter like a heart with skipped beats. I have sent chant-figures and hydrographs, and I will lend you an apprentice who hears stone as if it were rain, but you must keep them from any dispute that would set their throat to shouting. Do not allow the survey to become spectacle, nor the ledge to become a court, because both draw crowds and crowds draw tragedy. Return with a map of pulses and intervals, and we will write a counter-hymn of respect rather than an anthem of conquest.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Aren Siltwarden\", \"lines\": \"I have r